Now I see the issue. The `parse_grep_args` function tokenizes the input and matches known flags. Unknown tokens get pushed into `remaining_parts`. The first remaining part becomes the pattern, and the rest becomes the path.

So if the model passes `--json`, it would end up in `remaining_parts` and become part of the path. Then `run_grep` would construct a grep command like `grep -rn ... --json` which grep would interpret as its own flag.

The fix should be to intercept known grep-incompatible flags (like `--json`, `--jsonl`, or any flag that grep doesn't support but the model might emit) and either produce a clear error message or strip them before passing to grep.

